description:
lib.rs:106-122 (get) and lib.rs:149-163 (put) repeat the same shape for mapping keyring::Error variants:
- NoEntry → NotFound (only in get; not relevant for set_password)
- NoStorageAccess → Unavailable
- everything else → Backend

Plus the JoinError → Backend arm at lib.rs:125-128 and 166-169 is identical.

Idiomatic Rust extracts this as a private helper:

  fn map_keyring_err(e: keyring::Error) -> SecretError {
      match e {
          keyring::Error::NoStorageAccess(src) => SecretError::Unavailable { backend: "desktop", source: src },
          other => SecretError::Backend { backend: "desktop", source: other.into() },
      }
  }

  fn map_join_err(e: tokio::task::JoinError) -> SecretError {
      SecretError::Backend { backend: "desktop", source: e.into() }
  }

Why it matters: when fixing issue 1 (PlatformFailure → Unavailable on Linux), the fix needs to land in both get and put. With the helper, one place; without it, two places to update consistently — and easy to forget the second.

Cross-crate: secretx-keyring/src/lib.rs has the identical duplication.
